    To Dale and Stuart

    Actually I wanted do you a favour to Show how a Inline Assembler for Powerbasic 64 could Look Like. And its perhaps interesting for other Powerbasic Users too. Made a big Break Here over ten years cause I Had other priorities Like Family Job etcpp.. So I havent used Powerbasic a Lot Last years..

    I have different Versions Made in different Basic languages and its Not a Problem to correct right brackets Here in my Last Code example. Or the asm Help topic some days ago you could Post it there.
    If you criticise some Points its OK for me cause I am Not very familiar with Powerbasic Inline Assembler as I told you before. I have Made already an example its running under 64 Bit for another Basic language and it Works with right brackets and without..


    Code:
    #COMPILE EXE
#DIM ALL
'#include once "winapi64.inc" ' fictive

FUNCTION PBMAIN () AS LONG

LOCAL val1,val2,result AS LONG
val1=7
val2=9

'' Inline Assembler '''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''
' '' 32 bit
' ! mov eax,val2 ''multiply eax by ebx
' ! mul val1 'ebx
' ! mov result,eax
'''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''

'' 64 bit asm fictive -------------------------- //
! mov rax,val2
! mul val1
! mov result, rax
'' 64 bit asm fictive -------------------------- //

? "the result of " & STR$(val1) & " *" & STR$(val2) & " is " & STR$(result) '63

LOCAL tit AS STRING
LOCAL pTit AS LONG
tit = " PowerBASIC"
pTit = STRPTR(tit) ' Get the pointer after filling the string!

END FUNCTION
    I am curious to see whats going on Here with the Forum and Liked the friendly Kind since I have started at the Forum and Got a Lot of Help and inspiration about programming Hope the best again for Powerbasic .. more I havent to say

    I asked my AI friend to share it's thoughts, here is what it listed FWIW...

    Using a 64-bit compiler for creating 64-bit executables offers several significant benefits over a 32-bit compiler, particularly in the context of PowerBASIC or any other development environment. Here are the key advantages:

    1. Increased Memory Access
    • Larger Address Space: A 64-bit application can address significantly more memory compared to a 32-bit application. While a 32-bit application is limited to 4GB of RAM (and realistically around 2-3GB due to system and reserved space), a 64-bit application can theoretically address up to 16 exabytes of RAM, although current operating systems and hardware limit this to a lower, but still significantly larger, amount.
    2. Enhanced Performance
    • Registers and Operations: 64-bit processors have more and wider general-purpose registers. This allows for more efficient processing of data and can lead to performance improvements, especially in computation-heavy applications.
    • Optimized Execution: Some computations and operations can be performed more efficiently on 64-bit systems due to the availability of 64-bit arithmetic and the ability to handle larger integers natively.
    3. Future-Proofing
    • Modern Software and Hardware: As hardware and software ecosystems continue to evolve, there is a growing shift towards 64-bit architectures. Compiling your applications in 64-bit ensures compatibility with future hardware and software advancements, and takes full advantage of modern computing capabilities.
    • Deprecation of 32-bit: Many modern operating systems are phasing out or reducing support for 32-bit applications. By adopting 64-bit, you ensure that your applications remain supported on the latest operating systems.
    4. Security Enhancements
    • Enhanced Security Features: 64-bit systems often include additional security features such as improved Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR), Data Execution Prevention (DEP), and support for more advanced encryption algorithms. These features make 64-bit applications more secure against various types of attacks.
    5. Compatibility and Integration
    • Interoperability with Modern Libraries and Tools: Many modern libraries, APIs, and tools are optimized for 64-bit systems. Using a 64-bit compiler ensures better compatibility and performance when integrating with these modern resources.
    Specific to PowerBASIC
    • Large Data Handling: If your applications handle large datasets or require intensive computations, the increased memory and performance capabilities of 64-bit will be particularly beneficial.
    • Complex Applications: For applications that involve complex data structures, databases, or graphics processing, the advantages of 64-bit become more pronounced.
    Considerations
    • Legacy System Compatibility: If you need to support legacy systems that are only 32-bit, you might still need to maintain a 32-bit version of your application.
    • Dependency Compatibility: Ensure that all libraries and dependencies your application relies on are available and compatible in 64-bit versions.

    Overall, transitioning to a 64-bit compiler for your PowerBASIC applications can provide substantial benefits in terms of performance, memory management, security, and future-proofing your software.
